=== Lesson 31-1 (Introduction) ===

 {"type":"h3","text":"Germaine's Guide to RC Complete the Passage Questions"}
 {"type":"h4","text":"What's this question asking?"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Complete the Passage questions ask you to select the sentence that would most logically conclude the passage or a specific paragraph..."}
 {"type":"list","items":["Synthesize the main point of the final paragraph.","Reinforce the overall argument of the entire passage.","Provide a final, logical implication of the reasoning just presented.","Avoid introducing new, unsupported topics or contradicting earlier points."]}
 {"type":"hr"}
 {"type":"h3","text":"Stem Identification: How to Spot a Complete the Passage Question"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"These questions are easily recognizable because their stems explicitly ask you to add a sentence to the end of the text..."}
 {"type":"breakdown","labels":{"title":"Category","text":"Examples & Keywords"},"items":[
   {"title":"Logical Continuation Phrasing","text":"...complete, conclude, continuation, appended to the end...","badge":"Continuation","badgeColor":"indigo"}
 ]}
 {"type":"callout","title":"Overarching Takeaway","variant":"summary","text":"Your task is to identify the \"next logical thought.\"..."}
 {"type":"h3","text":"The Importance of Complete the Passage Questions"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Complete the Passage questions are the rarest type, appearing only 5 times in the dataset..."}
+{{+**Strategic note:** With only 5 appearances across all released LSATs, this is the lowest-priority question type for dedicated study. However, the underlying skill -- understanding how an author's argument builds to a conclusion -- directly strengthens your performance on Structure/Function and Paragraph Function questions, which are far more common.+}}

{ "type": "diff-note", "text": "The single stem category is appropriate -- this question type has an extremely narrow phrasing range. No additional categories needed.", "variant": "comment" }

=== Lesson 31-2 (Step-by-Step Approach) ===

 {"type":"h3","text":"Step-by-Step Approach"}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 1: Identify the Role of the Final Paragraph"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Before reading the answer choices, re-read the final paragraph and determine its specific function..."}
 {"type":"list","items":["Providing a final piece of evidence?","Proposing a solution to a problem raised earlier?","Summarizing the main argument?","Discussing the implications or future of the topic?"]}

{ "type": "diff-note", "text": "Step 1's four diagnostic questions are excellent. They give students concrete categories for paragraph function, which is a skill that transfers to other question types.", "variant": "comment" }

 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 2: Predict the Logical Next Thought"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Based on the paragraph's function, anticipate what the final sentence should accomplish..."}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 3: Test Each Answer Choice Against Your Prediction and the Passage's Scope"}
 {"type":"list","items":["**Logical Flow:**...","**Paragraph Cohesion:**...","**Passage Scope:**...","**Tone Consistency:**..."]}
+{{~change~}} The four evaluation criteria in Step 3 would be more scannable as a table:

| Criterion | What to Check | Elimination Signal |
|-----------|---------------|-------------------|
| Logical Flow | Follows from previous sentence | Abrupt topic shift |
| Paragraph Cohesion | Concludes the paragraph's point | Doesn't fit the paragraph's role |
| Passage Scope | Stays within passage topics | Introduces new concepts |
| Tone Consistency | Matches author's established tone | Sudden shift in register |

+{{+**Try this:** Attempt the question before reading the analysis below.+}}
